\par \pard\plain \s254\li115\sa120\sl-320 \b\f6\lang1033 \page {\plain \f6\fs18\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f6\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 $} Configure Comm...}} {\plain \f6\fs18\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain 
\s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f6\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 #} Configure_comm}} {\plain \f6\fs18\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f6\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 K} Configure Communications}} Configure Comm...
\par \pard\plain \li90\sb80\sl-240 \f6\fs20\lang1033 Brings up a dialog box allowing you to select communications/networking options.  
\par An earlier version of WinVN allowed you to choose between TCP/IP and straight serial connections.  Unadulterated serial connections are no longer supported; you must be running some 
brand of TCP network driver on your PC in order to use WinVN.  The network driver must be loaded before you start WinVN.  WinVN supports network drivers that conform to the Winsock interface; this includes products from a number of companies, including FT
P Software, Inc.  A separate DEC Pathworks version of WinVN is available.
\par The Configure Comm... dialog box requires you to fill in the Internet address of a {\ul news server}{\v news_server}.   Obtain this information from your system administrator.  You must also fi
ll in the TCP port number of the news server program.  Typically this is 119; other values can be used if your local news server is so configured.
\par Fill in the Internet address of a mail server if you plan on using mail from within WinVN.  
\par Some {\ul NNTP}{\v nntp} news servers require you to provide an authorizing username and password before they will allow you full access to some or all {\ul newsgroups}{\v newsgroup}
.  If you plan on connecting with such a server, you should fill in the appropriate username and password for the server you have selected.
\par See {\uldb Saving Configuration Information}{\v saving_configuration_information} and {\uldb Authorizing Yourself to the News Server}{\v\uldb authorizing_yourself_to_the_news_server}.
\par \pard\plain \s254\li115\sa120\sl-320 \b\f6\lang1033 \page {\plain \f6\fs18\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f6\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 $} Configure Personal Info...}} {\plain \f6\fs18\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain 
\s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f6\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 #} configure_personal_info}} {\plain \f6\fs18\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f6\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 K} Configure Personal Info}} Configure Personal Info...
\par \pard\plain \li90\sb80\sl-240 \f6\fs20\lang1033 Brings up a dialog box allowing you to specify personal information:  your name, electronic mail address, and organiza
tion name.  The organization name is typically the name of your employer or educational institution.  This information is used to construct {\ul headers}{\v header} for {\ul articles}{\v article} and {\ul electronic mail messages}{\v 
electronic_mail_message} that you write.
\par See {\uldb Saving Configuration Information}{\v saving_configuration_information}. 
\par \pard\plain \s254\li115\sa120\sl-320 \b\f6\lang1033 {\plain \f6\fs18\up6\lang1033 \page }{\plain \f6\fs18\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f6\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 $} Configure Miscellaneous}} {\plain \f6\fs18\up6\lang1033 
#{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f6\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 #} configure_miscellaneous}} {\plain \f6\fs18\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f6\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 K} Configure Miscellaneous}}
 Configure Miscellaneous
\par \pard\plain \li90\sb80\sl-240 \f6\fs20\lang1033 Brings up a dialog box allowing you to specify miscellaneous preferences regarding the operation of WinVN.
\par If {\i New window for each group} is checked, WinVN will attempt to create a new {\uldb group window}{\v group_window} for each {\ul newsgroup}{\v newsgroup} selected from the {\uldb main window}{\v main_window}
.  If this option is not checked, WinVN will reuse an existing group window to display newly-requested newsgroups.
\par If {\i New window for each article} is checked, WinVN will attempt to create a new {\uldb article window}{\v article_window} for each {\ul article}{\v article} selected from the {\uldb main window}{\v main_window}
.  If this option is not checked, WinVN will reuse an existing article window to display newly-requested articles.
\par Checking {\i Append saved articles} affects what WinVN does when you attempt to save the contents of an article to an existing file.  If this box is checked, WinVN will append the article to the file.  Otherwise, it will ask you what to do.  See {\uldb 
File Menu Commands}{\v file_menu_commands}. 
\par The {\i Check for new groups on startup} option determines whether WinVN queries the {\ul news server}{\v news_server} for newly-created {\ul newsgroups}{\v newsgroup}
.  Checking for new newsgroups also allows WinVN to determine which groups have received new articles since the last WinVN session.  The Yes and No options are self-explanatory; Ask means that WinVN will ask the user whether to check for new groups every 
time it starts up.  The Yes option is recommended for Ethernet-attached PCs.  Checking for new groups can take a very long time on serially-attached PCs, though.
\par See {\uldb Saving Configuration Information}{\v saving_configuration_information}.  
\par \pard\plain \s254\li115\sa120\sl-320 \b\f6\lang1033 \page {\plain \f6\fs18\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f6\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 $} Configure Logging...}} {\plain \f6\fs18\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain 
\s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f6\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 #} configure_logging}} {\plain \f6\fs18\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f6\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 K} Configure Logging}} Configure Logging...
\par \pard\plain \li90\sb80\sl-240 \f6\fs20\lang1033 Brings up a dialog box allowing you to specify whether all outgoing posts or mail messages should be logged to a local text file.  If you enable these options, you must also specify the file names to which {
\ul postings}{\v posting} or {\ul electronic mail messages}{\v electronic_mail_message} should be written.  
